erated on drug-related charges--Johnson insists that the decriminalization of marijuana and the elimination of mandatory minimums are among the first and most logical steps for the US to take toward creating a more sensible--and cost-effective--approach toward drug use.<BR><BR>"Should smoking marijuana in the confines of your own home, doing no harm arguably to anyone but yourself, be criminal?" he asks. "My fundamental belief is no, it should not be criminal. We cannot lock up 80 million Americans--the estimate of those Americans who have used drugs."<BR><BR>Gov. Johnson's sense of outrage about the Drug War has tapped into a growing sense of statewide and national outrage. In New Mexico, polls show that two-thirds of the people now support eliminating criminal penalties for possession of small amounts of marijuana and providing treatment, not incarceration, for users of harder drugs. And according to a March poll by the Pew Research Center for the People & the Press, three-fourths of Americans now think that the nation is losing the War on Drugs, and that drug use in the US will never be stopped. Fully one-half of those polled were of the opinion that drug addiction should be treated as a disease, not a crime.<BR><BR>Furthermore, said Johnson, the idea of marijuana as a gateway drug is absurd. "Statistically speaking, out of 105 marijuana users, one ends up as a user of cocaine," he emphasized. "As trite as this sounds, is milk a gateway to alcohol?<br><BR><BR><P ALIGN="right">by Silja J.A. Talvi, Special to HighWitness News</FONT></P><br></FONT></font>

